# Level 2 — Give it room to breathe

Look at your page. Every block is glued to the one above it. Cramped pages feel cheap, and the fix is one property: [`margin`](http://localhost:3031/d05-margin) — space on the **outside** of a box, where nothing else is allowed to sit.

## Do this

1. Push your sections apart from the outside:
   ```css
   section {
     margin: 24px;
   }
   ```
   Refresh. Everything unsticks at once.
2. Now prove the difference between the two kinds of space. Give something that **isn't** the whole page its own colour behind it — your intro paragraph is perfect:
   ```css
   p {
     background: #1e293b;
     padding: 12px;
     margin: 24px;
   }
   ```
3. Refresh and stare at it. The colour fills the **padding** and stops at the edge of the box. The **margin** stays uncoloured — margin is a force field, not a floor.
4. Say the sentence out loud so it sticks: *padding grows the box, margin grows the gap.*

> 💡 `margin: 24px` puts 24 pixels on all four sides. [`margin: 24px 0`](http://localhost:3031/d05-shorthand) means top/bottom 24, left/right 0. Two numbers, four sides.

⚠️ The background has to be on something other than [`body`](http://localhost:3031/d04-aiming). Colouring the whole page was Day 4 — today you're colouring a *box*.

**Your anchors:** a `margin:` somewhere in [`style.css`](http://localhost:3031/d04-two-files), and a [`background`](http://localhost:3031/d04-properties) inside a rule whose selector isn't `body`.

## ✅ You pass when

- [ ] Uses margin to push things apart
- [ ] Something that isn't the body has a background colour

