# Level 3 — The nav bar nobody has to be told about

Scroll to the top of your page. Your menu links are still stacked in a sad little column. Every real website on earth puts its menu in a horizontal row — and now you know exactly how they do it, because it's the same one property.

## Do this

1. In [`index.html`](http://localhost:3031/d01-index-html), look at the [`<nav>`](http://localhost:3031/m1-anatomy). It holds three [`<a>`](http://localhost:3031/d03-a) links. The `<nav>` is the container; the links are the children. Same shape as the card row.
2. In [`style.css`](http://localhost:3031/d04-two-files), add a rule for `nav` itself — not `nav a`, which you already have:
   ```css
   nav {
     display: flex;
     justify-content: center;
     gap: 12px;
   }
   ```
3. Save → refresh. That's a nav bar. That's the same nav bar every site you use has.
4. Now finish the card row properly — three cards, evenly sized, evenly spaced, deliberate:
   ```css
   .card-row {
     display: flex;
     justify-content: space-between;
     gap: 20px;
   }
   .card {
     flex: 1;
   }
   ```
   Keep all three cards in the row, and make sure each one is about your topic — real headings, real sentences.

> 💡 `nav { }` and `nav a { }` are two different rules doing two different jobs: one lays out the bar, the other styles the links inside it. You need both.

⚠️ If your links end up in a row but squashed against each other, you wrote `nav a { display: flex }` by mistake. The container is `nav`.

**Your anchors:** a `nav` rule with [`display: flex`](http://localhost:3031/d06-display-flex), a `.card-row` rule with `display: flex`, and three elements with [`class="card"`](http://localhost:3031/d05-card) in `index.html`.

## ✅ You pass when

- [ ] The nav itself is a flex row
- [ ] The `.card-row` is a flex row
- [ ] Three cards live in the row

