# Level 2 — Make it glide

Your hover works, and it *snaps*. On/off, like a light switch. That's the difference between a page that looks like a school project and one that looks like a product: professionals make the change take a fraction of a second.

One property. One line. And the whole lesson is **where you put it**.

## Do this

1. Get it wrong on purpose first — it takes ten seconds and you'll never forget it. Put the line inside your [`:hover`](http://localhost:3031/d07-hover) rule:
   ```css
   nav a:hover {
     background: #38bdf8;
     transition: background 0.3s;   /* ← the wrong home */
   }
   ```
   Refresh. Hover on: it glides in. Hover off: it *slams* back. Half-broken, which is worse than broken.
2. Now move it to the **normal** rule and delete it from the `:hover`:
   ```css
   nav a {
     color: #38bdf8;
     border: 1px solid #38bdf8;
     padding: 6px 12px;
     transition: background 0.3s;   /* ← its actual home */
   }

   nav a:hover {
     background: #38bdf8;
   }
   ```
3. Refresh. Smooth in, smooth out.

> 💡 **Why:** [`transition`](http://localhost:3031/d07-transition) is a property of the *element*, not of the hover. It means "whenever this thing's background changes, take 0.3 seconds about it." If it only exists inside `:hover`, it vanishes the moment the mouse leaves — so there's nothing left to run the animation backwards.

Tuning: `0.15s` feels snappy, `0.3s` feels right, `1s` feels like the page is buffering. List more than one property with a comma: `transition: background 0.3s, color 0.3s;`

**Your anchors:** a `transition:` line in [`style.css`](http://localhost:3031/d04-two-files), on the normal rule.

## ✅ You pass when

- [ ] Uses transition so the change glides instead of snapping

# Level 3 — Polish, everywhere, on purpose

One glowing nav is a trick. A site where *everything* behaves the same way is a design. Time to take the two lines that make anything look expensive — rounded corners and a shadow — bottle them as a class, and put reactions on the cards too.

## Do this

**Part 1 — the button look.** Those two links in the `actions` block are pretending to be buttons and doing a bad job of it. Build one rule they can share:

```css
.btn {
  color: #0f172a;
  background: #38bdf8;
  text-decoration: none;
  font-weight: bold;
  padding: 10px 18px;
  border-radius: 999px;
  box-shadow: 0 4px 10px rgba(56, 189, 248, 0.35);
  transition: background 0.3s, box-shadow 0.3s;
}

.btn:hover {
  background: #7dd3fc;
  box-shadow: 0 8px 18px rgba(56, 189, 248, 0.6);
}
```

Then in [`index.html`](http://localhost:3031/d01-index-html), hang the class on **both** links:

```html
<a class="btn" href="#one">Read the broth rules</a>
```

Decode `box-shadow: 0 4px 10px rgba(...)`: no sideways offset, 4px down, 10px of blur, in a see-through colour. Bigger blur and more offset on hover = the thing looks like it lifted off the page. That's the whole illusion.

`border-radius: 999px` is a joke that works — any number bigger than the box gives you a perfect pill.

**Part 2 — the cards.** Same treatment, in your [`.card`](http://localhost:3031/d05-card) rule:

- add [`border-radius`](http://localhost:3031/d05-shorthand) and a [`box-shadow`](http://localhost:3031/d07-shadow)
- add a [`transition`](http://localhost:3031/d07-transition) (in the normal rule — Level 2 rules still apply)
- add a `.card:hover` rule that changes the background and pushes the shadow bigger

**Part 3 — mean it.** Pick one accent colour for your topic and use it in *every* hover on the page. Consistency is the thing being marked here, not the specific colours.

⚠️ [`.btn`](http://localhost:3031/d07-btn) in CSS has a dot; `class="btn"` in HTML doesn't. Both links need it — one isn't a system.

**Your anchors:** a `.btn` rule containing `border-radius` and `box-shadow`, `class="btn"` on two elements in `index.html`, a `.card:hover` rule, and a `transition:` inside the `.card` rule.

