# Level 3 — Build an actual tool

Echoing text is a demo. A **tool** is something a person would genuinely open. Input → logic → answer on the page: that's every calculator, budgeter and planner ever shipped, and tomorrow's major project is exactly this, bigger.

## Do this

1. **Pick your tool.** It has to be about something you care about, and it has to take one number and give back one number. Four to steal:

   | Tool | `toolResult(n)` does |
   |---|---|
   | 🃏 Pack-opening cost | `n` packs × price × 1.13 tax = what your wallet loses |
   | 🐴 Horse feed planner | `n` horses × scoops per day × days = total scoops |
   | 👟 Sneaker resale profit | resale price × `n` pairs − what you paid = profit |
   | 💪 Workout rep counter | `n` sets × reps × weight = total kilos moved |

2. **Write the brain, outside the browser block.** `toolResult` takes a number and hands back a **number** — no text, no [`textContent`](http://localhost:3031/d14-text-content), no printing:
   ```js
   const PACK_PRICE = 5.99;

   function toolResult(packs) {
     const beforeTax = packs * PACK_PRICE;
     return Math.round(beforeTax * 1.13 * 100) / 100;
   }
   ```
   (That `Math.round(... * 100) / 100` trick chops the answer to 2 decimal places — money shouldn't have 7 digits after the dot. 🔭 `Math.round` is on the [reference sheet](reference/js-reference.md).)
3. **Wire it up, inside the browser block.** Read the number box, [`Number()`](http://localhost:3031/d15-number) it, feed it in, show the answer in one line:
   ```js
   document.getElementById("count-button").addEventListener("click", function () {
     const packs = Number(document.getElementById("number-input").value);
     resultBox.textContent = `${packs} packs = $${toolResult(packs)} after tax. Your wallet is crying.`;
   });
   ```
4. Try `1`. Try `12`. Try `100`. Then hand your laptop to a classmate and watch them use it without any instructions from you. That's the real test.

> 🔍 The checker calls `toolResult` with amounts you can't see and checks that **different inputs give different answers** — so it must actually do math on `n`, not return the same number every time.

**Your anchors:** `toolResult(n)` returning a number; a line that puts `toolResult(...)` into `textContent`.

## ✅ You pass when

- [ ] toolResult(n) gives back a real number, and different inputs give different answers
- [ ] The page displays the answer from toolResult(...)

