# Level 4 — 🧩 The ✖ that knows who it belongs to

Every item in your list gets its own little **✖** button. Click the one next to "Starter Pack" and *only* "Starter Pack" disappears.

> 🤔 **Why this is Level 4:** you're making buttons inside a loop, which means you're making a *pile of identical buttons*. So how does button number 4 know it's button number 4? Nobody has shown you this. You have to reason about the index — the slot number — and realise it's the only thing that tells one item apart from another. Bonus: your remove function can't just "delete" something, because you've never been taught how. You'll build the answer out of a loop and an [`if`](http://localhost:3031/d13-if).

## Part 1 — the brain

Outside the browser block, finish [`removeAt(list, index)`](http://localhost:3031/d20-remove). It returns the list **without** the thing at slot `index`:

- `removeAt(["a","b","c"], 1)` → `["a","c"]`
- `removeAt(["x","y"], 0)` → `["y"]`

You have no "delete" tool. So flip the problem around: **don't remove the bad one — keep all the good ones.** Start an empty list, loop the old one, and push everything whose slot number *isn't* `index`. Three lines you already know how to write.

## Part 2 — the wiring

Inside [`render()`](http://localhost:3031/d20-render), while you're building each [`<li>`](http://localhost:3031/d02-li), build a ✖ button too:

```js
const slot = i;                                   // ← remember WHICH one this is
const killer = document.createElement("button");
killer.className = "kill";
killer.textContent = "✖";
killer.addEventListener("click", function () {
  items = removeAt(items, slot);
  render();
});
row.appendChild(killer);
```

That `const slot = i;` line is the whole puzzle. The click happens *later* — long after the loop has finished and moved on — so the button needs its own private copy of the slot number to carry around. Every button ends up holding a different one, and that's how it knows.

Then it's the same three moves as always: **change the array → `render()` → done.** The list redraws, and every remaining item gets fresh buttons with fresh slot numbers. Nothing to keep in sync.

Call it exactly as `removeAt(items, slot)` — the checker looks for `removeAt(items,` so the stub sitting there alone can't fool it.

> 😈 Flex (not checked): make the ✖ ask "are you sure?" first, or make removed items go to a `<ul id="graveyard">` instead of vanishing. Same array-in-page-out pattern, twice.

**Your anchors:** `removeAt(list, index)` — already declared in the starter, tested with lists you've never seen — wired up as `removeAt(items, …)`.

