# Level 4 — 🔎 Find it

Every search bar you have ever used — Spotify, Netflix, your contacts, the Pokédex — is this function. You type a name, something walks a list of objects, and it hands back **the whole record**, not just the word you typed. Build it.

> 🤔 **Why this is Level 4:** nobody showed you a searching loop. You have to combine three separate skills — a loop (Day 18), a decision (Day 13), and objects (today) — and get the *return* right: the matching **object**, not [`true`](http://localhost:3031/d13-else), not the index, not the name. And when nothing matches you must return [`null`](http://localhost:3031/d21-find) instead of quietly returning nothing. That last part is what separates a working search bar from a broken one.

## Do this

1. Find the **Level 4** section. Make `findByName` walk `list`, compare each member's `name` to `name`, and hand back the member that matches:
   ```js
   function findByName(list, name) {
     for (let i = 0; i < list.length; i = i + 1) {
       if (list[i].name === name) {
         return list[i];   // the WHOLE object, not just the name
       }
     }
     return null;          // walked the whole list, found nothing
   }
   ```
   The `return null` goes **after** the loop. Put it inside and your search gives up after one look.
2. Use it for real — search your roster and describe whoever turns up:
   ```js
   const found = findByName(roster, "The Waffle");
   if (found === null) {
     show("Nobody by that name on this roster.");
   } else {
     show(`FOUND: ${describe(found)}`);
   }
   ```
3. Search for a name that isn't there. You should get your polite "nobody" message instead of a crash. That's a real feature.

> 💡 The checker searches rosters you've never seen and reads properties you never wrote (like `hp`) off whatever you hand back — the only way to pass is to return the actual object you found.

**Your anchors:** `findByName(list, name)` — already declared in the starter. Returns the matching object, or `null`.

